<DocsLayout
  title="Trust Model"
  description="How GPG identity tiers, capability pins, and Ed25519-signed audit compose into the trust model. Four problems an operator has — what can I do, how do I graduate, how do I verify a release, how do I revoke a compromised key — and the compositions that solve them."
  sectionLabel="REFERENCE // TRUST"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-8">
    Trust composes from three layers: GPG-rooted identity tiers (who you are), capability pins (what you can touch), and Ed25519-signed audit (what you actually did). Below: four problems, four compositions, then the model.
  </p>

  <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    The kernel determines your tier at boot — no UI, no flags, just GPG state. T0 anchors are hardcoded in the binary (ceremony cannot reach T0). T1 is cross-signed write access; T2 is GPG-without-cross-sign; T3 is anonymous. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- Problem 01 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_01 // WHAT_CAN_I_DO_AS_INSTALLED</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I just installed ostk. What's the default?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      <strong class="text-on-surface">T3 — anonymous, read-everything, write-blocked.</strong> Without a GPG key you can boot, observe the fleet, run commands that don't mutate, and read every file in <code class="text-primary">.ostk/</code>. Writes through kernel verbs (<code class="text-primary">fs_ops</code>, <code class="text-primary">bash</code> with redirect, <code class="text-primary">run</code>) are denied by the deny-all default in pin caps. The kernel announces your tier on every <code class="text-primary">ostk boot</code> — no ambiguity about what you have.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk boot
trust: <span class="text-primary">T3</span> (anonymous, read-only)
HUMANFILE: not found
boot confidence: 0.30 (restricted mode)</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Tier resolver (no GPG → T3) · pin caps with <code class="text-primary">deny write-everything</code> default · Owned State (invariant II) — there's no UI override for tier; the kernel decides.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> (tier resolver), <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code> (pin cap evaluation).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 02 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_02 // GRADUATE_TO_WRITE</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I want to graduate from anonymous to write-capable on a project.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Two-step ceremony. First, generate a GPG key — that gets you to <strong class="text-on-surface">T2</strong> (GPG present but uncrossed; reads everything, narrow write exceptions per pin caps). Second, get someone at T1 or T0 to cross-sign your key — that gets you to <strong class="text-on-surface">T1</strong> (write access on the project they cross-signed for). The cross-signature is checked at boot via <code class="text-primary">gpg --check-sigs</code>; if it's there, the kernel reads your tier as T1.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline"># T3 → T2: generate a GPG key</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>gpg --full-generate-key
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk boot
trust: <span class="text-primary">T2</span> (read + narrow exceptions)

<span class="text-outline"># T2 → T1: have a T0 or T1 holder cross-sign your key</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk trust sign &lt;your-fingerprint&gt;     <span class="text-outline"># run by the cross-signer</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk boot
trust: <span class="text-primary">T1</span> (cross-signed, write access)</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl mb-4">
      <strong class="text-on-surface">T0 is unreachable by ceremony.</strong> T0 fingerprints are hardcoded in <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> and shipped with the binary. To gain T0 your fingerprint has to land in a kernel release — that's the substrate's anchor of last resort.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        GPG key generation · cross-signature ceremony · <code class="text-primary">ostk trust sign</code> verb · kernel boot-time tier resolution · T0 hardcoded anchor list (5 fingerprints in v4.4.x).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/trust.rs</code> (sign / rotate / revoke), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> (T0_TRUST_ANCHORS, <code>check_gpg_cross_signature</code>).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 03 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_03 // VERIFY_BEFORE_INSTALL</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I want to verify what I'm about to install.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Three layers compose. <strong class="text-on-surface">Binary signatures</strong> — every released tarball ships with an <code class="text-primary">.asc</code> GPG signature against the operator's release key, the install script verifies before extracting. <strong class="text-on-surface">Bail packages</strong> — <code class="text-primary">ostk bail verify</code> walks the embedded audit chain, checks every prev_hash and Ed25519 row signature, confirms the package contents match what was signed. <strong class="text-on-surface">Local audit</strong> — once installed, <code class="text-primary">ostk os audit</code> verifies your local journal end-to-end at any time. The verification path doesn't rely on trusting ostk; it relies on the math.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline"># Binary install: signature checked automatically by install.sh</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>curl -fsSL https://ostk.ai/install.sh | sh
verifying GPG signature... ok

<span class="text-outline"># Verify a bail package someone sent you</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk bail verify ./incoming.bail
chain: 412 rows, prev_hash continuous, sig verified, T0 anchor matches

<span class="text-outline"># Verify your own journal</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk os audit
audit: 18,442 rows, hash chain ok, signatures verified</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Release-asset GPG signatures (.asc) · bail's embedded chain + Ed25519 row signatures · <code class="text-primary">os audit</code> replay · T0 anchor list as the verification root. No external CA, no network call.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/bail.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/os.rs</code> (audit subcommand), <code class="text-primary">src/util/audit.rs</code> (hash chain), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/signing.rs</code> (Ed25519 in-process).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 04 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_04 // REVOKE_A_COMPROMISED_KEY</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">My private key leaked. How do I revoke it without losing history?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      The audit chain stays intact; what changes is what the substrate trusts going forward. <code class="text-primary">ostk trust revoke</code> records a revocation event in the journal — keyed by content hash and fingerprint, signed by an authority key (T0 if you can reach one, T1 with cross-sign capability otherwise). The kernel reads the revocation list at boot; rows signed before revocation remain valid (they were valid at write time) but the revoked key can no longer sign new rows. Generate a fresh key, get it cross-signed, you're back to T1 under a new identity.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline"># Record the revocation</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk trust revoke &lt;compromised-fingerprint&gt; --reason "leak 2026-04-26"

<span class="text-outline"># Cut a fresh key, restart the ceremony</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>gpg --full-generate-key
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk trust sign &lt;new-fingerprint&gt;       <span class="text-outline"># run by a T0/T1 holder</span></pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Revocation event in the journal (content-hash + fingerprint) · authority signature on the revocation · kernel boot-time revocation list check · audit chain unchanged (history is what it was, signed at write time).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/trust.rs</code> (revoke subcommand), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> (revocation list), <code class="text-primary">docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md</code> Invariant III on the unchangedness of past audit rows.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The composition -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">THE_COMPOSITION</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Three layers compose into the trust model.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-6">
      Every problem above composes the same three layers. Identity says <strong class="text-on-surface">who you are</strong>; capability pins say <strong class="text-on-surface">what you can touch</strong>; the audit chain says <strong class="text-on-surface">what you actually did</strong>. The kernel doesn't ask you to trust it — it gives you the math to verify each layer.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-px bg-surface-variant max-w-3xl mb-6">
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-5">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">IDENTITY</div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">Four GPG-rooted tiers. T0 hardcoded; T1 cross-signed; T2 GPG-without-cross-sign; T3 anonymous.</p>
        <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-outline">
          <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-5">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">CAPABILITY</div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">Pin caps deny by default. Tier sets the floor; <a href="/docs/pins/" class="text-primary hover:underline">pin caps</a> set the ceiling.</p>
        <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-outline">
          <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-surface-container p-5">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">AUDIT</div>
        <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-3">Every action hash-chained, Ed25519-signed in-process. Replay with <code class="text-primary">ostk os audit</code>.</p>
        <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-outline">
          <code class="text-primary">src/util/audit.rs</code>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl mb-4">
      Why three? Because each layer fails differently, and a security model that conflates them is brittle. Identity tells you who's at the keyboard; pins tell you what they can do <em>at this moment</em>; audit tells you what they actually did. Identity can be revoked without invalidating history. Pins can change per project without changing identity. Audit is append-only and signed at write time — yesterday's truth doesn't change because today's keys did.
    </p>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline italic max-w-xl">
      One historical note: GPG remains canonical for tier determination; Ed25519 is for per-action audit signing. The rationale: GPG carries cross-signing semantics (web of trust) that Ed25519 doesn't, and the operator's GPG keyring is the system the operator already trusts. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> doc-comment.
    </p>
  </section>

